f imperial coercion, but of a people’s language in a postcolonial democracy.Focusing on experiences of hearing, touching, remembering, speaking, and seeing English, Akshya Saxena delves into a previously unexplored body of texts from English and Hindi literature, law, film, visual art, and public protests. She reveals little-known debates and practices that have shaped the meanings of English in India and the Anglophone world, including the overlooked history of the legislation of English in India. She also calls attention to how low castes and minority ethnic groups have routinely used this elite language to protest the Indian state.Challenging prevailing conceptions of English as a vernacular and global lingua franca, Vernacular English does nothing less than reimagine what a language is and the categories used to analyze it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2022) 0aEnglish languagexSocial aspectszIndia. 0aIndic literature (English)y20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLanguage policyzIndiaxHistoryy20th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Comparative Literature.2bisacsh  aAcousmatic sound.  aAdmiration.  aAmbedkar.  aAmericans.  aAnonymity.  aAo Naga.  aAudre Lorde.  aBangladesh.  aBollywood.  aBrahmin.  aBreast.  aBritish Empire.  aCaste.  aCess.  aClothing.  aCoercive logic.  aColonialism.  aCommodity.  aCriticism.  aDalit (poem).  aDalit studies.  aDalit.  aDebt.  aDichotomy.  aDisenchantment.  aDistrict Administration.  aElision.  aEtymology.  aFemale infanticide in India.  aForgetting.  aGovernance.  aGovernment of Uttar Pradesh.  aGovernmentality.  aHat tip.  aHegemony.  aHindi.  aHindu nationalism.  aHindu.  aHistoriography.  aHomophone.  aHow-to.  aHumiliation.  aIn Plain Sight.  aIndology.  aIrony.  aJawaharlal Nehru